
PLENOR.AI
Site Configuration Standard

Version 1.0 — Current Phase
Required Dependent Instrument of the Plenor.ai Website Specification v1.0

Instrument Identity and Governing Relationship
This document is the Plenor Site Configuration Standard. It is a required dependent instrument of the Plenor.ai Website Specification, current phase. It is subordinate to the Website Specification in governance terms but authoritative over the governed configuration model within its domain, including configuration object structures, rules, validation logic, completion criteria, and implementation/CMS controls insofar as they resolve, expose, or apply that governed model. Both instruments must be satisfied. Neither overrides the other within its own domain. Changes to this document are subject to the same change control discipline as the Website Specification.

SECTION 1 — PURPOSE, SCOPE, AND RELATIONSHIP
1. Purpose, Scope, and Relationship
1.1 Purpose
This document defines the governed configuration model for the plenor.ai website. It is the authoritative source for the configuration object structures, rules, validation logic, and completion criteria that the site’s active configuration must satisfy. Technology changes, CMS replacements, and front-end framework changes do not alter the governed configuration model. Implementations must conform to it.

1.2 Scope
This document defines the governed structure, rules, and completion requirements for six configuration categories. The active values for each category are defined in the Site Configuration Record:
•	Category 1 — Design Configuration: Family, Scheme, Preset objects, Typography Usage Configuration, Current Design Selection, and Design Rules
•	Category 2 — Identity and Brand Values: company identity, contact details, logo and favicon assets, policy text, copyright
•	Category 3 — Navigation Values: primary and secondary navigation labels, order, and mobile pattern
•	Category 4 — Content Ordering and Display Fallback Values: homepage fallback rules, tiebreaker rules, minimum content thresholds, FAQ placement governance
•	Category 5 — Operational Values: lifecycle labels, workflow labels, form text, messaging, date format, implementation-scope decisions
•	Category 6 — SEO and Metadata Values: metadata defaults, canonical rules, robots rules, sitemap rules, structured data mappings, social sharing assets

1.3 Relationship to the Website Specification
The Website Specification governs what configuration categories must exist, what rules apply to them, and what constraints their entries must satisfy. This document governs the configuration model that the actual configuration entries must conform to. The active values themselves are defined in the Site Configuration Record.

Authority Rule
This document is authoritative over all implementation and CMS controls insofar as they resolve, expose, or apply the governed configuration model. Implementations must conform to this document. This document does not conform to implementations.

SECTION 2 — GOVERNING PRINCIPLES AND MODEL RULES
2. Governing Principles and Model Rules
2.1 Governance compliant
Every entry in this document must be explicitly traceable to a governing section of the Website Specification. Untraceable entries must not be introduced.

2.2 Simple and clean
The model uses the minimum structural complexity needed to govern the site correctly. Fields are not added without justified governance need.

2.3 Sophisticated in output
Simplicity in the model does not permit low-design output. The governed values must produce a site that is visually distinguished, typographically rigorous, and professionally credible.

2.4 Scalable and evolvable
The model must accommodate future Families, Schemes, Presets, and non-design configuration entries without structural rewrite. Extensibility must be achieved by adding governed entries, not by relaxing governance rules.

2.5 AI and code-gen readable
Every object, field, and rule must be defined with sufficient precision that an AI model or code generation tool can read this document and produce compliant implementation output without ambiguity.

2.6 Extensibility rule
A new Family, Scheme, Preset, or non-design configuration object may be added to this document through governed revision. The addition must not conflict with existing governed entries and must satisfy all applicable rules in the Website Specification.

2.7 Completion rule
This document is considered complete when all configuration categories defined in Website Specification §8.6.3 have governed configuration entries, each required entry is assigned a value or explicitly marked as out of scope, deferred, or not used in the current phase, naming conventions are defined and applied consistently, and all applicable entries satisfy the accessibility constraints defined in Website Specification §8.6.7.

SECTION 3 — STRUCTURAL MODEL
3. Structural Model
The Site Configuration Model has two structural zones:
•	Design Configuration Objects — uses richer instantiated objects because it contains layered Family, Scheme, and Preset relationships
•	Non-Design Configuration Objects — uses structured configuration objects appropriate to each category

3.1 Design Configuration Objects
The design zone contains the following governed object types:
Object	Purpose
Family	Highest-level design archetype; defines the broad design universe
Scheme	Concrete visual theme within a Family; contains colors, layout, buttons, emailPalette, shadowElevation, motion, and preset references
Typography Preset	Full text role hierarchy with size, weight, line height, and spacing values
Typography Usage Configuration	Governed mapping between content/interface elements and text roles
Spacing Preset	Spacing rhythm and density — base unit, scale, section and hero padding variants
Radius Preset	Shape language — button radius, card radius, optional general scale
Current Design Selection	Active state — which Family, Scheme, and Presets are currently selected
Design Rules	Governed operating logic — selection rules, validation rules, lifecycle rules

3.2 Non-Design Configuration Objects
The non-design zone contains the following governed object types:
Object	Governing Spec Section
Identity and Brand Configuration Object	§8.6.3 Category 2
Navigation Configuration Object	§8.6.3 Category 3
Content Ordering and Display Fallback Configuration Object	§8.6.3 Category 4
Operational Configuration Object	§8.6.3 Category 5
SEO and Metadata Configuration Object	§8.6.3 Category 6

SECTION 4 — DESIGN CONFIGURATION MODEL
4. Design Configuration Model
4.1 Family
A Family is the highest-level design archetype. Its purpose is to define the broad design universe for a site type.

A Family contains:
Field	Required / Optional	Description/Rule
key	Required	Unique identifier among all Family objects
label	Required	Human-readable name
description	Required	Purpose and character of this Family
allowedSchemes	Required	List of valid Scheme keys; every Scheme in this list must have parentFamily equal to this Family key
status	Required	From the governed status set — see Appendix C

4.2 Scheme
A Scheme is the concrete visual theme object within a Family. Its purpose is to define the actual visual system used by the site.

A Scheme contains:
Field	Required / Optional	Description/Rule
key	Required	Unique identifier among all Scheme objects
label	Required	Human-readable name
description	Required	Visual character and intended use
parentFamily	Required	Must reference one valid Family
colors	Required	Semantic color roles — see §5.1
layout	Required	Layout constraints and breakpoint values — see §5.2. Breakpoint values in Scheme.layout are the authoritative governed definitions. Website Specification §9.5 must conform to these values.
buttons	Optional/Minimal	Button-specific values where not derivable from colors and radius preset — see §5.3
emailPalette	Optional	Channel-specific email styling values — see §5.4
shadowElevation	Required where used; otherwise explicitly marked `Not Used in Current Phase` or `Deferred`	Governed elevation and shadow definition for this Scheme. This field either defines the approved elevation and shadow treatment for the Scheme or explicitly records that such a system is not used in the current phase.
motion	Required	Governed motion definition for this Scheme. It must define named transition duration values, named easing functions, and the reduced-motion handling rule that implementations must honor.
allowedTypographyPresets	Required	List of Typography Preset keys allowed for this Scheme
defaultTypographyPreset	Required	Must be one member of allowedTypographyPresets
allowedSpacingPresets	Required	List of Spacing Preset keys allowed for this Scheme
defaultSpacingPreset	Required	Must be one member of allowedSpacingPresets
allowedRadiusPresets	Required	List of Radius Preset keys allowed for this Scheme
defaultRadiusPreset	Required	Must be one member of allowedRadiusPresets
status	Required	From the governed status set
notes	Optional	Governed interpretive notes

4.3 Preset
A Preset is a reusable bundle of values for one design dimension. The current model uses three preset subtype classes:
•	Typography Preset — text hierarchy, font families, and role-level values
•	Spacing Preset — spacing rhythm, section padding, and mobile padding
•	Radius Preset — shape language for buttons, cards, and general radius scale

Each preset subtype is governed as its own object structure and must not be treated as an untyped generic.

4.4 Current Design Selection
Current Design Selection stores the currently active design configuration state for the site.

Field	Required / Optional	Description/Rule
currentFamily	Required	Must reference an existing Family
currentScheme	Required	Must reference an existing Scheme allowed by currentFamily
currentTypographyPreset	Required	Must be one of the allowedTypographyPresets of currentScheme
currentSpacingPreset	Required	Must be one of the allowedSpacingPresets of currentScheme
currentRadiusPreset	Required	Must be one of the allowedRadiusPresets of currentScheme

Lifecycle Rule
A deprecated Scheme or Preset may not be newly selected as current active state. If a Scheme or Preset becomes deprecated while still active, it remains valid until it is replaced through a governed change. Replacement must be completed before the deprecated entry is removed from the model.

4.5 Design Rules
Design Rule objects define the governed operating logic of the design model. These include selection rules, defaulting rules, override rules, validation rules, lifecycle rules, and extensibility rules.

At minimum, the model must validate that:
•	every value in Family.allowedSchemes resolves to an existing Scheme
•	every Scheme.parentFamily resolves to an existing Family
•	every value in Scheme.allowedTypographyPresets resolves to an existing Typography Preset
•	every value in Scheme.allowedSpacingPresets resolves to an existing Spacing Preset
•	every value in Scheme.allowedRadiusPresets resolves to an existing Radius Preset
•	every default preset reference resolves to an existing approved preset record of the correct subtype
•	every Scheme listed in a Family.allowedSchemes set has parentFamily equal to that Family
•	defaultTypographyPreset is one member of allowedTypographyPresets
•	defaultSpacingPreset is one member of allowedSpacingPresets
•	defaultRadiusPreset is one member of allowedRadiusPresets
•	currentTypographyPreset is one member of the allowedTypographyPresets of the currentScheme
•	currentSpacingPreset is one member of the allowedSpacingPresets of the currentScheme
•	currentRadiusPreset is one member of the allowedRadiusPresets of the currentScheme
every Scheme must define `shadowElevation` or explicitly mark it `Not Used in Current Phase` or `Deferred`
every Scheme must define `motion`
every Scheme.motion entry must define named transition duration values
every Scheme.motion entry must define named easing functions
implementations using Scheme.motion values must honor reduced-motion accessibility requirements

4.6 Typography Preset
A Typography Preset must define a full text hierarchy, not just one font and one base size.

Field	Required / Optional	Description/Rule
key	Required	Unique identifier
label	Required	Human-readable name
bodyFontFamily	Required	Primary body font family
displayFontFamily	Optional	Display font family if different from body
textRoles	Required	Governed text role set — see below
status	Required	From the governed status set

The controlled text roles for the current model are:
Text Role	Intended Usage
display	Hero or lead statements requiring a larger visual treatment
h1	Primary page heading — one per page unless governed exception is defined
h2	Major section headings under the page heading
h3	Subsection headings under an H2
body	Standard paragraph content
bodySmall	Secondary supporting text
label	Eyebrow text, section labels, tags, small UI labels
button	Button text where separate button typography treatment is governed
quote	Quotation text, pull quotes, or highlighted quoted statements
quoteAttribution	Attribution line associated with quote text

Each text role contains:
Field	Required / Optional	Description/Rule
fontSize	Required	Font size value
fontStyle	Required	Font style value — allowed values: normal, italic, oblique
lineHeight	Required	Line height value
fontWeight	Required	Font weight value
letterSpacing	Optional	Letter spacing where relevant

Semantic Heading Rule
Display styling may be applied visually to a heading, but semantic heading level must still follow the document structure. A page should normally use one H1 as its primary heading unless a governed exception is explicitly defined.

4.7 Typography Usage Configuration
Typography Usage Configuration defines the governed mapping between content or interface elements and the text roles provided by the active Typography Preset.

Field	Required / Optional	Description/Rule
homepageHeroTitle	Optional	May map to display; semantic heading level must still follow page structure
homepageHeroSupportingText	Optional	Typically body or bodySmall
pageTitle	Required	Should normally map to h1
sectionTitle	Required	Should normally map to h2
subsectionTitle	Required	Should normally map to h3
bodyParagraph	Required	Should normally map to body
supportingText	Optional	Typically bodySmall
eyebrowLabel	Optional	Typically label
buttonText	Required	Should normally map to button
cardTitle	Optional	Typically h3 or label depending on card type
cardSummary	Optional	Typically bodySmall
faqQuestion	Optional	Typically body or label
faqAnswer	Optional	Typically body
quoteText	Optional	Should normally map to quote
quoteAttribution	Optional	Should normally map to quoteAttribution

Fallback Rule
Where an optional Typography Usage Configuration field is absent, the implementation must apply a governed fallback: absent optional mappings resolve to the nearest semantic text role — display and heading elements fall back to the nearest heading role below them; body and supporting elements fall back to body; UI elements fall back to label or button as appropriate. Where quote-related optional mappings are absent, quoted content falls back to body and quote attribution falls back to bodySmall unless a governed mapping is defined. Absent optional fields must not produce unmapped elements in the implementation.

