SECTION 6 — CONFIGURATION RESOLUTION AND CONTROL
6. Configuration Resolution and Control
6.1 Configuration flow
The active configuration is resolved as follows:

Non-design configuration is read from the five governed non-design configuration objects.

Design configuration resolves through the following sequence:
•	The selected Family determines which Schemes are allowed through Family.allowedSchemes
•	The selected Scheme must belong to the allowedSchemes set of the current Family
•	The selected Scheme supplies colors, layout, buttons, emailPalette, shadowElevation, motion, allowed preset sets, and default preset references
•	The current Typography, Spacing, and Radius Presets are initialized from the selected Scheme defaults
•	If the role and rule set permit it, the current presets may be changed to another allowed preset within the allowed set of the current Scheme
The final active site configuration is:
•	all five non-design configuration objects
•	currentFamily
•	currentScheme
•	scheme colors, layout, buttons, emailPalette, shadowElevation, and motion
•	currentTypographyPreset
•	currentSpacingPreset
•	currentRadiusPreset

6.2 Configurability model
The model defines the following configurability classes:
Class	Meaning
Fixed	Value is set by governance and may not be changed without governed revision
Selectable	Value may be changed to another approved option within the governed allowed set
Override Allowed	Value has a governed default but may be overridden within approved boundaries
System Managed	Value is managed by the platform or CMS system within governed constraints

No field or entry may use a configurability class outside the allowed mapping for its responsibility. See Appendix D for the full configurability mapping.

6.3 Entry types
The configuration document uses these entry types:
Entry Type	Used For
Allowed Set Entry	Defining which values are permitted within an allowed set
Current Selection Entry	Recording which value is currently active
Default Mapping Entry	Recording the default value before any override or selection
Rule Entry	Defining governing logic — canonical rules, robots rules, sitemap rules
Value Entry	Defining a specific governed value — metadata defaults, labels, text
Asset Entry	Referencing a governed asset — logo, favicon, social sharing image
Mapping Entry	Defining a correspondence between two governed sets — structured data mappings, typography usage mappings

